UNCLE SADDAM (DVD5, 2000)

Everything you've always wanted to know about Saddam Hussein

(but were afraid to ask)

( = WINNER = ) Best Documentary, New Orleans Film Festival

( = WINNER = ) Best Documentary, Northampton Film Festival

Uncle Saddam is a satirical yet sobering look inside the world of Iraqi president Saddam Hussein. Award winning filmmaker Joel Soler, who is still under U.S. Government protection, risked life and limb to shoot and smuggle this strange and captivating footage out of Iraq. Featuring narration written by Scott Thompson of the Kids in the Hall, and the voice of Wallace Langham (&quot;The Larry Sanders Show&quot;), the film has the feel of an episode of &quot;Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous&quot; spotlighting, as is often the case, one of the world's most hated men.

SPECIAL FEATURES:

Interview with director Joel Soler
Saddam's Family Tree
Full-length interview with Saddam's interior decorator (executed shortly thereafter)
Animated menus, Chapter selection, Original trailer.

NTSC DVD5 4:3 Runtime: 63m, special features 40m approx.

&quot;Intriguing and bizarre...paints Saddam as the genocidal Jerry Seinfeld. The madness of kings was never this mad.&quot; ~ Maureen Dowd, The New York Times

&quot;Wryly amusing, yet dreadfully alarming. A devastating portrait of a megalomanic.&quot;
~ Barry Garron, The Hollywood Reporter

&quot;Burn the satanic movie, or you will be dead.&quot;
 ~ Anonymous critic who vandalized the home of filmmaker Joel Soler

